101
00:06:05,077 --> 00:06:06,576
in these flux ropes.

102
00:06:07,024 --> 00:06:10,820
We can observe that the complex 
3D magnetic field can develop

103
00:06:10,820 --> 00:06:13,623
in which opposite directed
magnetic fields

104
00:06:13,623 --> 00:06:16,236
are brought together by plasma flows.

105
00:06:18,559 --> 00:06:22,028
For example, let's suppose
that in this flux rope

106
00:06:22,096 --> 00:06:25,352
the magnetic field is oriented
in the following way

107
00:06:26,279 --> 00:06:30,851
and the plasma flow with a velocity v
is squeezing the flux rope.

108
00:06:33,044 --> 00:06:34,451
In a second time,

109
00:06:34,589 --> 00:06:39,304
we can observe that the complex 
3D magnetic field can develop

110
00:06:39,304 --> 00:06:42,029
in which opposite directed
magnetic fields

111
00:06:42,029 --> 00:06:44,234
are brought together by the plasma flow,

112
00:06:44,244 --> 00:06:47,300
and they start to interact 
in a small region.

113
00:06:48,189 --> 00:06:51,423
In the following we will see 
that magnetic reconnection

114
00:06:51,423 --> 00:06:54,753
is the basis of the interaction

115
00:06:54,753 --> 00:06:56,967
of oppositely directed field lines.

116
00:06:58,086 --> 00:07:02,594
To describe the interactions
of magnetic fields,

117
00:07:02,594 --> 00:07:06,494
let's go back to the resistive
MHD equations

118
00:07:06,494 --> 00:07:08,678
that you have seen in previous modules.

119
00:07:09,592 --> 00:07:14,824
The key parameter in this equation
is the <i>magnetic Reynolds number</i>

120
00:07:14,824 --> 00:07:20,139
which in most astrophysical systems
is much larger than 1.

121
00:07:20,139 --> 00:07:23,588
Let's suppose that we start
from a situation

122
00:07:23,588 --> 00:07:27,147
where we have an opposite directed
magnetic field lines

123
00:07:27,147 --> 00:07:29,048
as shown in this picture,

124
00:07:29,048 --> 00:07:33,129
which are embedded in a plasma
with the magnetic Reynolds number

125
00:07:33,129 --> 00:07:34,738
much larger than 1.

126
00:07:34,738 --> 00:07:39,638
Now, we push the magnetic field lines,
one against the other

127
00:07:39,827 --> 00:07:43,975
by using a plasma flow
with a velocity v.

128
00:07:44,268 --> 00:07:48,621
Which are the consequences 
of a large magnetic Reynolds number?

129
00:07:49,051 --> 00:07:53,394
The advection dominates 
the plasma dynamics.

130
00:07:54,363 --> 00:07:58,860
Therefore, the magnetic field lines
are frozen in the plasma

131
00:07:58,860 --> 00:08:01,547
and the ideal MHD holds.

132
00:08:02,301 --> 00:08:06,209
This means that the magnetic 
diffusivity term

133
00:08:06,209 --> 00:08:07,740
can be neglected.

134
00:08:08,429 --> 00:08:12,969
Another important consequence
of a magnetic Reynolds number, very large

135
00:08:12,969 --> 00:08:18,492
is that the magnetic flux is frozen
to the plasma motion

136
00:08:18,492 --> 00:08:22,793
and therefore, the magnetic field lines
cannot break or reconnect.

137
00:08:23,228 --> 00:08:28,349
This means that no changes 
in the magnetic topology are allowed.

138
00:08:29,593 --> 00:08:32,180
If we keep pushing 
the magnetic field lines

139
00:08:32,180 --> 00:08:33,665
with a velocity v

140
00:08:34,106 --> 00:08:36,571
then we get closer and closer

141
00:08:36,571 --> 00:08:40,870
and the magnetic flux 
will be compressed between them.

142
00:08:41,763 --> 00:08:45,726
This in turn will increase 
the magnetic field gradient

143
00:08:45,726 --> 00:08:50,471
which are characterized 
by the special distance d

144
00:08:50,471 --> 00:08:53,806
and as a consequence,
the magnetic Reynolds number

145
00:08:53,806 --> 00:08:56,076
will be decreased in a small layer

146
00:08:56,076 --> 00:08:59,650
across the opposite directed 
magnetic field lines.

147
00:09:02,530 --> 00:09:06,492
Therefore, very thin regions can form

148
00:09:06,492 --> 00:09:09,450
where the gradients 
of the magnetic fields are very large.

149
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:16,133
In this thin region, a current develops
in the perpendicular plane,

150
00:09:16,270 --> 00:09:20,225
and the ideal MHD does not hold anymore.

151
00:09:21,427 --> 00:09:25,971
In this very thin region 
where the ideal MHD is violated,

152
00:09:25,971 --> 00:09:28,535
magnetic reconnection can happen.

153
00:09:29,006 --> 00:09:32,607
A magnetic field line which is pushed
by the plasma flow

154
00:09:32,607 --> 00:09:36,467
against a magnetic field line
which is opposite directed,

155
00:09:36,590 --> 00:09:41,895
will break and reconnect, thus forming
a new magnetic field line.

156
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:46,417
Which are the consequences 
of magnetic reconnection?

157
00:09:46,809 --> 00:09:51,670
As you can see, the global topology
of the magnetic field now has changed

158
00:09:51,670 --> 00:09:55,637
and this affects the path of particles
and heat conduction.

159
00:09:56,137 --> 00:09:58,897
As we will see in the following slides,

160
00:09:58,897 --> 00:10:02,978
the magnetic energy is converted 
into heat, kinetic energy

161
00:10:02,978 --> 00:10:04,890
and fast particles energy.

162
00:10:05,097 --> 00:10:06,679
During magnetic reconnection,

163
00:10:06,781 --> 00:10:09,601
large electric currents 
and fields are generated

164
00:10:09,601 --> 00:10:11,093
at the reconnection sites,

165
00:10:11,093 --> 00:10:14,445
as well as shocks, waves 
and filamentation.

166
00:10:15,949 --> 00:10:19,818
Let's now describe 
the magnetic reconnection dynamics

167
00:10:19,818 --> 00:10:23,468
using a simple model, 
the <i>Sweet-Parker model,</i>

168
00:10:23,515 --> 00:10:27,859
that was originally proposed 
by Sweet in 1958

169
00:10:27,933 --> 00:10:30,419
and by Parker in 1957.

170
00:10:30,968 --> 00:10:33,403
This was the first quantitative model

171
00:10:33,403 --> 00:10:36,961
of magnetic reconnection to be developed.

172
00:10:39,955 --> 00:10:44,235
The geometry of the Sweet-Parker model
is represented here.

173
00:10:45,492 --> 00:10:50,908
Opposite directed field lines
with magnetic field intensity B₀

174
00:10:50,908 --> 00:10:56,374
are brought together by a plasma flow
with a velocity v₀

175
00:10:56,988 --> 00:11:02,255
They form a current sheet
of length 2L and thickness 2d

176
00:11:02,397 --> 00:11:03,486
shown here in red.

177
00:11:03,997 --> 00:11:06,756
Reconnection happens 
in the the current sheet

178
00:11:07,236 --> 00:11:09,754
and the new magnetic field lines

179
00:11:09,754 --> 00:11:14,697
are now flowing out of the current sheet
with the velocity vout

180
00:11:14,803 --> 00:11:17,977
and a magnetic field intensity, Bout

181
00:11:19,212 --> 00:11:21,926
To derive the model,
we made the following hypotheses:

182
00:11:21,997 --> 00:11:23,677
Outside the current sheet,

183
00:11:23,677 --> 00:11:27,231
the magnetic Reynolds number
is much larger than 1.

184
00:11:27,696 --> 00:11:31,420
Inside the current sheet,
the plasma has a resistivity

185
00:11:31,420 --> 00:11:33,774
indicated by eta (η).

186
00:11:34,135 --> 00:11:36,402
The system is in steady state,

187
00:11:36,402 --> 00:11:39,670
