the outflow plasma velocity

246
00:15:25,718 --> 00:15:29,515
and by recalling the definition
of the Alfvén speed

247
00:15:29,515 --> 00:15:34,405
we obtain this important result
that the plasma is accelerated

248
00:15:34,405 --> 00:15:37,355
at the Alfvén speed 
by reconnection process.

249
00:15:39,833 --> 00:15:44,088
If we now define the <i>Lundquist number</i>
which is an dimensionless number

250
00:15:44,088 --> 00:15:46,985
and we recall the formulas
that we have derived so far,

251
00:15:47,470 --> 00:15:50,507
we have fully characterized 
the current sheet

252
00:15:50,507 --> 00:15:52,425
in the Sweet-Parker model.

253
00:15:53,377 --> 00:15:57,051
In particular, we obtained 
that the inflow velocity

254
00:15:57,051 --> 00:15:59,449
is equal to the Alfvén speed

255
00:15:59,449 --> 00:16:02,521
divided by the square root
of the Lundquist number.

256
00:16:03,018 --> 00:16:08,575
And the current sheet geometry
defined the ratio d/L

257
00:16:08,575 --> 00:16:13,391
scales like 1 over the square root
of the Lundquist number.

258
00:16:14,375 --> 00:16:16,578
Since in astrophysical systems

259
00:16:16,578 --> 00:16:20,072
the Lundquist number 
is usually much larger than 1,

260
00:16:20,072 --> 00:16:23,600
this formula tells us 
that in the Sweet-Parker model

261
00:16:23,600 --> 00:16:26,211
the current sheet is very thin.

262
00:16:27,767 --> 00:16:32,340
And this formula tells us that the plasma
is flowing into the current sheet

263
00:16:32,340 --> 00:16:36,432
with the velocity which is much smaller
than the Alfvén speed.

264
00:16:38,817 --> 00:16:42,418
Let's now do some energy
considerations.

265
00:16:43,310 --> 00:16:47,211
In the Sweet-Parker model,
the sheet is thin and elongated.

266
00:16:47,924 --> 00:16:52,981
The plasma outflows
from the current sheet at Alfvén velocity.

267
00:16:54,111 --> 00:16:58,179
We can also compute the magnetic field
at the exit of the current sheet

268
00:16:58,179 --> 00:17:00,972
using the flux conservation.

269
00:17:01,616 --> 00:17:05,255
And we obtain that it is much smaller
than the magnetic field,

270
00:17:05,255 --> 00:17:07,285
than the entrance of the magnetic field,

271
00:17:07,291 --> 00:17:10,297
since it scales like 1 
over the square root

272
00:17:10,297 --> 00:17:11,940
of the Lundquist number.

273
00:17:13,459 --> 00:17:17,390
Let's now recall the flux
of the electromagnetic energy

274
00:17:17,390 --> 00:17:20,088
is given by the <i>Poynting flux</i>.

275
00:17:20,088 --> 00:17:24,579
And let's compute the Poynting flux
at the edge of the current sheet.

276
00:17:24,579 --> 00:17:30,426
We have obtained this expression
by recalling that E = v₀ B₀.

277
00:17:30,426 --> 00:17:34,505
We can now use this expression
to compute the ratio

278
00:17:34,505 --> 00:17:39,483
of the kinetic energy flux
by the magnetic energy flux.

279
00:17:46,162 --> 00:17:49,128
Recalling that the inflow plasma velocity

280
00:17:49,128 --> 00:17:52,383
is much smaller than the Alfvén velocity

281
00:17:52,383 --> 00:17:57,812
we can easily conclude
that most of the inflow energy

282
00:17:57,812 --> 00:17:59,842
is of magnetic nature.

283
00:18:00,617 --> 00:18:04,248
What about the outflow
in magnetic energy?

284
00:18:04,848 --> 00:18:06,722
This can be easily estimated,

285
00:18:06,937 --> 00:18:11,224
and by recalling that Bout
is much smaller than B₀,

286
00:18:11,335 --> 00:18:14,505
and small d is much smaller than L,

287
00:18:14,505 --> 00:18:17,708
we obtain the result that
the outflowing magnetic energy

288
00:18:17,708 --> 00:18:20,162
can be neglected.

289
00:18:21,101 --> 00:18:25,661
Let's now compute the ratio
of the outflowing kinetic energy flux

290
00:18:25,661 --> 00:18:28,587
to the inflowing magnetic energy flux.

291
00:18:30,379 --> 00:18:34,768
We obtain the important result
that during magnetic reconnection

292
00:18:34,768 --> 00:18:36,828
in the simple Sweet-Parker model,

293
00:18:36,828 --> 00:18:39,297
half of the incoming magnetic energy

294
00:18:39,297 --> 00:18:42,886
is converted into plasma kinetic energy.

295
00:18:44,208 --> 00:18:45,749
I will not demonstrate it,

296
00:18:45,749 --> 00:18:50,973
but the other half is converted
into heat by Joule dissipation.

297
00:18:51,435 --> 00:18:54,189
Therefore, the reconnection layers

298
00:18:54,284 --> 00:18:58,458
act as a source of hot and fast plasma.

299
00:19:01,234 --> 00:19:03,822
How fast is this process?

300
00:19:03,822 --> 00:19:08,892
The plasma enters the current sheet
at the velocity v₀.

301
00:19:08,892 --> 00:19:10,410
This is also the rate

302
00:19:10,410 --> 00:19:14,074
at which the magnetic flux enters
the current sheet.

303
00:19:14,167 --> 00:19:17,514
In this region, the plasma slips 
from the magnetic fields

304
00:19:17,514 --> 00:19:21,703
and flow out at the Alfvén speed 
along the current sheet.

305
00:19:22,351 --> 00:19:25,233
No more plasma can enter
and carry magnetic flux

306
00:19:25,233 --> 00:19:27,413
until the previous one has left.

307
00:19:28,295 --> 00:19:31,513
An important parameter to define

308
00:19:31,513 --> 00:19:35,093
how fast the reconnection is happening

309
00:19:35,093 --> 00:19:37,464
is the so-called <i>Reconnection rate</i>.

310
00:19:37,669 --> 00:19:42,494
This is defined as the ratio
of the incoming flow velocity

311
00:19:42,494 --> 00:19:44,298
to the outcoming flow velocity.

312
00:19:44,711 --> 00:19:50,598
And in the Sweet-Parker model
it is equal to v₀ / vAlfvén.

313
00:19:50,598 --> 00:19:52,832
This shows that in the Sweet-Parker model

314
00:19:52,832 --> 00:19:56,676
the reconnection rate scales like
the inverse of the square root

315
00:19:56,676 --> 00:19:58,489
of the Lundquist number.

316
00:19:58,489 --> 00:20:01,621
Since the Lundquist number 
is much larger than 1

317
00:20:01,621 --> 00:20:04,002
for many astrophysical systems,

318
00:20:04,002 --> 00:20:07,750
The Sweet-Parker rate leads
to reconnection times

319
00:20:07,750 --> 00:20:12,137
that are many orders of magnitude
larger than those that are observed.

320
00:20:13,135 --> 00:20:16,323
If we want to accelerate 
the reconnection rate,

321
00:20:16,323 --> 00:20:21,030
and you increase v₀ externally
from the outside

322
00:20:21,030 --> 00:20:23,542
for a fixed Lundquist number,

323
00:20:23,542 --> 00:20:26,044
the reconnection rate remains constant

324
00:20:26,044 --> 00:20:30,418
and therefore, the Alfvén velocity
must increase to maintain the same ratio.

325
00:20:30,561 --> 00:20:34,552
This is obtained by increasing
the Alfvén velocity

326
00:20:34,552 --> 00:20:37,927
by increasing the incoming magnetic field.

327
00:20:39,079 --> 00:20:42,898
Therefore, pushing the reconnection harder
from the outside,

328
00:20:43,344 --> 00:20:47,352
does not increase the reconnection rate
in the Sweet-Parker model

329
00:20:47,504 --> 00:20:50,283
but only compresses the magnetic field.

330
00:20:52,784 --> 00:20:55,955
Let's now apply the Sweet-Parker model

331
00:20:55,955 --> 00:21:00,384
to two examples 
of magnetic reconnection in nature.

332
00:21:01,018 --> 00:21:04,352
The first example 
is a <i>Coronal Mass Ejection.</i>

333
00:21:04,879 --> 00:21:08,024
A picture of a CME is shown here,

334
00:21:08,024 --> 00:21:10,598
where a beautiful prominence eruption

335
00:21:10,719 --> 00:21:15,542
produced a CME on April 16, 2012.

336
00:21:15,578 --> 00:21:21,026
Typical timescales for CME's 
are of the order of a hundred seconds.

337
00:21:21,866 --> 00:21:27,056
Magnetic reconnection 
is believed to be responsible for CME's.

338
00:21:27,056 --> 00:21:32,020
Let's try to estimate 
the reconnection time

339
00:21:32,020 --> 00:21:33,820
from the Sweet-Parker model

340
00:21:33,820 --> 00:21:36,106
using the following formula.

341
00:21:36,174 --> 00:21:38,432
If we plot typical numbers

342
00:21:38,432 --> 00:21:41,431
for a coronal mass ejection 
into this formula,

343
00:21:41,431 --> 00:21:47,112
we end up with a prediction
of a approximately 10⁷s

344
00:21:47,112 --> 00:21:50,855
which is much larger than
typical timescales

345
00:21:50,855 --> 00:21:52,995
which are usually observed.

346
00:21:53,099 --> 00:21:56,233
Therefore, the Sweet-Parker 
reconnection model

347
00:21:56,233 --> 00:22:00,424
produces a dynamics which is far too slow

348
00:22:00,424 --> 00:22:03,124
to describe coronal mass ejections.

349
00:22:04,942 --> 00:22:07,698
As a second example 
of magnetic reconnection,

350
00:22:07,791 --> 00:22:11,651
let's consider the 
<i>Sawtooth Instablity</i> in tokamaks,

351
00:22:11,651 --> 00:22:17,056
in which plasma energy and particles
are periodically expelled

352
00:22:17,056 --> 00:22:20,035
from the center of the plasma
towards the edge.

353
00:22:20,596 --> 00:22:25,696
This picture shows an example
of sawtooth in a TCV discharge

354
00:22:25,696 --> 00:22:29,634
[observed] using the central 
soft x-ray emission

355
00:22:29,634 --> 00:22:32,813
which is roughly proportional 
to the square

356
00:22:32,813 --> 00:22:35,890
of the electron density
and the electron temperature

357
00:22:35,890 --> 00:22:37,525
as a function of time.

358
00:22:38,392 --> 00:22:43,019
The central soft x-ray emissivity
drops dramatically

359
00:22:43,019 --> 00:22:48,159
over a very fast timescale 
during the so-called <i>sawtooth crash</i>.

360
00:22:48,159 --> 00:22:52,600
The poloidal cross-section profile
of the soft x-ray

361
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:55,317
before and after the sawtooth crash

362
00:22:55,317 --> 00:23:01,640
clearly displays the redistribution
of energy associated with sawteeth.

363
00:23:01,759 --> 00:23:05,008
Sawtooth crashes happen
on the TCV tokamak

364
00:23:05,008 --> 00:23:09,276
on timescales of the order of 10 
to 50 microseconds.

365
00:23:10,025 --> 00:23:14,650
This is the time during which 
magnetic reconnection occurs.

366
00:23:15,012 --> 00:23:19,218
If we estimate the Sweet-Parker
reconnection time

367
00:23:19,236 --> 00:23:23,382
using typical values for TCV plasmas,

368
00:23:23,382 --> 00:23:28,889
we obtain reconnection time
of the order between 1 and 10 millisecond

369
00:23:28,975 --> 00:23:34,053
which is too large if compared
with experimental values.

370
00:23:35,606 --> 00:23:39,631
In the two cases of magnetic reconnection
that we have seen,

371
00:23:39,631 --> 00:23:42,987
the Sweet-Parker rate is too slow.

372
00:23:44,581 --> 00:23:47,824
How can we go beyond Sweet-Parker?

373
00:23:48,696 --> 00:23:52,385
If we want to decrease
the reconnection time [τSP],

374
00:23:52,385 --> 00:23:56,826
we can, for example act
on the sheet thickness [L]

375
00:23:56,906 --> 00:23:59,973
by modifying the sheet geometry.

376
00:24:00,567 --> 00:24:04,691
One example is the <i>Petschek model</i>
for magnetic reconnection.

377
00:24:06,752 --> 00:24:10,647
Or, we could, for example increase
the resistivity

378
00:24:13,689 --> 00:24:16,525
by introducing turbulence

379
00:24:16,525 --> 00:24:21,050
which may give rise 
to anomalous resistivity.

380
00:24:22,130 --> 00:24:25,147
Or, we could introduce new physics
into our model

381
00:24:25,262 --> 00:24:29,923
by going for example beyond 
single fluid MHD

382
00:24:29,923 --> 00:24:33,223
Or, by introducing 
three dimensional physics.

383
00:24:34,528 --> 00:24:39,487
All these ways are the subjects
of intensive studies

384
00:24:39,620 --> 00:24:41,948
in the scientific community.

385
00:24:41,948 --> 00:24:46,802
However, a number of open question remains
for magnetic reconnection.

386
00:24:46,802 --> 00:24:51,644
Among the most important 
open questions are:

387
00:24:51,644 --> 00:24:55,760
"What are the causes
of the fast reconnection rate?"

388
00:24:56,131 --> 00:24:58,105
"How does reconnection start?

389
00:24:58,673 --> 00:25:02,435
And when it starts, 
how are particles accelerated and heated?"

390
00:25:02,538 --> 00:25:06,340
"What is the interplay between 
the small scale physics

391
00:25:06,340 --> 00:25:10,777
that happens in the current sheet
and the global dynamics of the plasma?"

392
00:25:11,593 --> 00:25:15,258
And probably 
one of the most difficult questions is

393
00:25:15,258 --> 00:25:19,101
"How can we model three-dimensional
magnetic reconnection?"

394
00:25:19,421 --> 00:25:22,333
To advance our understanding
in the future,

395
00:25:22,333 --> 00:25:26,467
we will need more observational data,
numerical simulations

396
00:25:26,467 --> 00:25:28,428
and laboratory experiments.

397
00:25:30,710 --> 00:25:33,393
As an example of numerical simulation,

398
00:25:33,393 --> 00:25:36,485
I show you here a movie, 
which is obtained

399
00:25:36,485 --> 00:25:39,406
from one of the most advanced 
numerical simulations

400
00:25:39,406 --> 00:25:41,009
of magnetic reconnection

401
00:25:41,009 --> 00:25:43,190
from a fully kinetic model.

402
00:25:43,190 --> 00:25:48,413
The simulation employed 
two trillion particles with 8 billion cells

403
00:25:48,413 --> 00:25:50,645
and was performed 
on the blue water machine

404
00:25:50,645 --> 00:25:52,725
at the University of Illinois.

405
00:25:52,725 --> 00:25:56,098
The movie shows the volume rendering
of the current density

406
00:25:56,098 --> 00:25:57,935
during the magnetic reconnection.

407
00:25:57,935 --> 00:26:03,066
The complexity of this process,
well-beyond the simple Sweet-Parker model

408
00:26:03,066 --> 00:26:07,253
is revealed by the development
of a fully three-dimensional turbulence

409
00:26:07,253 --> 00:26:09,325
in the current sheet.

410
00:26:09,967 --> 00:26:14,435
Numerical simulations are important
to shed light on reconnection physics.

411
00:26:15,022 --> 00:26:18,641
They must be compared 
against experimental data.

412
00:26:18,641 --> 00:26:23,081
These are difficult,
if not impossible to obtain

413
00:26:23,081 --> 00:26:27,389
from distance observations
using telescopes and satellites.

414
00:26:27,481 --> 00:26:33,059
An important role can be therefore played
by laboratory experiments

415
00:26:33,059 --> 00:26:38,076
which provide easy diagnostic access
and control experimental conditions.

416
00:26:38,501 --> 00:26:42,546
A number of magnetic reconnection
laboratory experiments

417
00:26:42,546 --> 00:26:44,513
has been developed in the past

418
00:26:44,513 --> 00:26:48,542
and is presently under development
with different geometries

419
00:26:48,565 --> 00:26:52,365
from two-dimensional
to fully three-dimensional

420
00:26:52,365 --> 00:26:55,284
and also covering different plasma regimes

421
00:26:55,284 --> 00:27:01,047
from Sweet-Parker to two-fluid MHD
and kinetic reconnection.

422
00:27:01,047 --> 00:27:04,212
These will provide an important test bed

423
00:27:04,212 --> 00:27:06,845
for reconnection theories and simulations.

424
00:27:08,125 --> 00:27:12,296
In this module, we have explored
the dynamics of solar flux tubes.

425
00:27:12,296 --> 00:27:15,147
They are advected by the plasma flow

426
00:27:15,147 --> 00:27:18,081
and their opposite magnetic fields 
reconnect,

427
00:27:18,081 --> 00:27:19,935
change the plasma topology,

428
00:27:19,935 --> 00:27:22,844
and dissipate the large amount
of magnetic energy

429
00:27:22,844 --> 00:27:26,545
that goes into particle acceleration
plasma heating.

430
00:27:27,165 --> 00:27:29,845
Although the basics 
of magnetic reconnection

431
00:27:29,845 --> 00:27:33,671
can be caught by the simple 
two-dimensional Sweet-Parker model,

432
00:27:33,671 --> 00:27:37,384
the predictions of the reconnection time
are not in agreement

433
00:27:37,384 --> 00:27:39,004
with experimental data

434
00:27:39,004 --> 00:27:41,269
which show much faster dynamics,

435
00:27:41,269 --> 00:27:46,139
for example, in coronal mass ejections
or sawteeth in tokamaks.

436
00:27:46,139 --> 00:27:50,342
In the future, advancing our understanding
of magnetic reconnection

437
00:27:50,342 --> 00:27:52,899
will require the use 
of observational data,

438
00:27:52,899 --> 00:27:56,573
sophisticated numerical simulation
and experiments

439
00:27:56,573 --> 00:27:59,869
in well controlled and diagnosed
laboratory devices.

440
00:27:59,869 --> 00:28:04,205
In the next module, we will explore
how the plasma dynamics in the Sun

441
00:28:04,205 --> 00:28:08,864
can shape the surrounding environment
by generating the solar wind.
